Section Summary: The author participated in a historic movement, sending 499 trained men and women to the Philippine Islands to establish a system of free public schools. This event, which took place on July 23, 1901, marked an epoch in world history as a conquering people sent educators instead of soldiers to a conquered land. The group traveled from San Francisco to Manila, stopping in Honolulu, where they experienced the local culture and saw notable sights such as the Pali and a collection of Hawaiian artifacts. Along the way, they crossed the International Date Line, resulting in the loss of a day, and eventually arrived in Manila, where they were introduced to the local customs and people. The author describes the challenging landing in Manila Bay and the group's initial impressions of the city and its inhabitants.
